Quoted By:
>>63768978
>Do you plan out your stories and have an written down overview of what you want, or do you just wing it with a GENERAL idea of what direction you are wanting the story to go?

All stories have a plan or at least a general theme, but we inevitably abandon part of it for something better or something we find more fun along the way. Just because your original plan was good or was supposedly bulletproof doesn't mean it can't be improved upon, deviated or more to give some callbacks, some nice moments or even some levity. Characters and their situations are why we read most of these things, so knowing what makes them tick and then how they respond can be a good basis for a story, but not the entire thing, winging it all usually leads to bad shit if the story goes for long.

In a tabletop system, you might be the GM and have unpredictable players being themselves, but as a writer, you are the GM and the players. You can make some shit up, but if you control the board, you should control their ending too, even if perhaps not how they get there.
